    <div class="team-callout creative" style="margin-top:18px">
      <span class="team-tag">Creative · Asset library access</span>
      <p style="margin:0">All approved Pizza Pack creative assets, founder b-roll, lifestyle photography, retail-shelf shots, and editable templates live in the Inventel shared brand drive under <code>/Pizza Pack/Creative/</code>. New hires on the Creative team should request access from the Creative Director on day one. Don't pull product images off the public website for paid ad work — request the high-res original from the asset library.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="team-callout marketing" style="margin-top:14px">
      <span class="team-tag">Marketing · What's worked, what's flopped</span>
      <p style="margin:0">UGC reaction-style content has been the strongest paid format for cold acquisition over the last 12 months. Long-form &quot;founder talking head&quot; ads underperform on cold but win on retargeting and lookalike audiences. Avoid &quot;life hack&quot; framing — Pizza Pack is a product, not a hack, and that framing has tested poorly with the As-Seen-On-TV audience. Lean into Shark Tank credibility, not life-hack tropes.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="team-callout newhire">
      <span class="team-tag">New Hire · How to recognize on-brand creative</span>
      <p style="margin:0">A creative is on-brand if (1) the pain is named in the first 3 seconds, (2) the demo is visible by second 5, (3) the setting is a real-feeling kitchen or fridge, (4) the copy uses casual rhythm (not corporate), and (5) there's exactly one CTA. If a creative misses any of those, send it back to revisions before approving.</p>
    </div>
